- If any business-critical issues present → Ben
- If technical issues without business-critical components → Jerry
- If only marketing/community items → Tom

4. Based on the analysis above, route to:
BEN for business-critical escalations
JERRY for technical implementation and bugs
TOM for marketing and community engagement

{"identifier": "cs_email:685036db", "prompt_str": "<TO_OPTIMIZE kind="User">
Analyze and route the following email using these steps:

Subject: {subject}
Body: {body}

1. First check for ANY of these CRITICAL business indicators that require routing to Ben:
- Press/media interaction or coverage of any kind
- Legal concerns or threats
- Security/privacy issues
- Customer complaints about staff or service
- Enterprise/large account discussions
- Investor relations
- Contract or billing concerns

2. If no critical indicators, check for technical issues (route to Jerry):
HIGH SEVERITY (always Jerry):
- System crashes or outages
- Data loss
- Authentication failures
- Performance emergencies

STANDARD TECHNICAL (Jerry if no business overlap):
- API/SDK questions
- Bug reports
- Implementation help
- Technical documentation
- Feature behavior questions

3. If no critical business or technical issues, route community/marketing items to Tom:
- General partnerships without business implications
- Community events
- Training/webinars
- Market research
- Social media

4. For mixed cases, use these priority rules:
a) ANY critical business indicator → Ben
b) High severity technical without business critical → Jerry
c) Standard technical + marketing → Jerry
d) Marketing only → Tom

Analyze the content thoroughly and output the routing decision in standard case: "ben", "jerry", or "tom"

{"identifier": "cs_email:36b0f65c", "prompt_str": "<TO_OPTIMIZE kind="User">
OVERRIDE TRIGGERS - Check these FIRST and STOP if found:
ANY mention of these topics MUST route to Ben regardless of other content:
- Press/Media/News/Reporter/Interview/Coverage
- Legal/Lawsuit/Attorney/Compliance
- Security/Privacy/Data breach/Access
- Investor/VC/Funding

If no override triggers, follow this strict hierarchy:

1. BUSINESS-CRITICAL (→ Ben)
Route to Ben if ANY of these business indicators present:
- Enterprise/Large account discussions
- Staff/Service complaints
- Contract/Billing/Account issues
- Strategic partnerships (involving competitors, revenue, or business terms)

2. TECHNICAL ISSUES (→ Jerry)
Only route here if NO business indicators above:
a) SEVERE Technical:
- System down/crash/outage
- Data loss/corruption
- Authentication broken
- Critical performance issues

b) Standard Technical:
- API/SDK questions
- Bug reports

  • Resource commitments
  • Technical integration
  • Long-term relationship
- Technical issues affecting revenue/enterprise

a) Core Infrastructure:
- System stability (crashes, outages, performance)
- Data integrity/loss

- API/SDK development
- Code-level issues
- Technical specifications
- Implementation guidance

b) Developer Documentation:

- Beta/technical changes
- Implementation guides

- Development tutorials
- Technical specifications

- Marketing automation
- Newsletter systems
- Webinar platforms
- Training delivery
- Social media tools

b) Market Research:
- Competitor evaluation (no strategic terms)
- Feature comparison
- Market analysis
- Partnership evaluation:
  • No revenue/resource commitments
  • Content/community focus
  • Market research only

c) User Content:
- Product usage guides
- Feature tutorials
- Best practices
- Training materials
- Community resources

EDGE CASE GUIDELINES:
• Documentation Classification:
  - If for developers/implementation → Jerry
  - If for users/usage → Tom

  - Always business relationship → Ben
  - Even if technically focused
• Partnership/Competition:
  - If involves commitments → Ben
  - If research/evaluation → Tom
• Tool-related issues:
  - If about infrastructure → Jerry
  - If about usage/features → Tom
